<text><front></front><body>
<pb facs="#f0001" />
    <div n="1"><head>OPINION OF HUMBOLDT.</head><lb/><p>The celebrated Baron Humboldt has written a<lb/>note to Dr. Franz Schegel, M. D. of <choice><sic>Altenbergh</sic><corr type="editorial">Altenburgh</corr></choice>,<lb/>Germany, in &#x201C;relation to the moving of tables.&#x201D;&#x2014;<lb/>He writes&#x2014;</p><lb/><p>&#x201C;It is easier to combat a theory than facts im-<lb/>perfectly observed. There are diseases
                    of belief<lb/>which return periodically, and are as endemical<lb/>with the
                    polished as with the lower classes, be-<lb/>cause in the former they assume the
                    form of dog-<lb/>matism and arrogance peculiar to the superficial.&#x2014;<lb/>I
                    tender you, most honored Doctor, my kindest<lb/>thanks for the publication of
                    your very simple<lb/>mechanical explanation of the turning of tables<lb/>towards
                    the north pole. But you will convert no-<lb/>body.</p><closer><salute>With the highest esteem, &#x0026;c.<lb/><hi rendition="#k">Alexander Von
                        Humboldt.</hi></salute></closer><lb/><dateline>Berlin, April 18, 1853.&#x201D;</dateline></div><lb/></body><back></back>

</text>
